## 5. The Scriptural Verdict on Those Who Reject the Evidence

The scriptures do not portray rejection of the resurrection as a neutral intellectual stance. They diagnose it as a moral and spiritual condition.

**Suppression of Truth:** Romans 1:18–21 states that God’s existence and power are clearly perceived, but humanity “by their unrighteousness suppress the truth.” The verb implies an active holding down of what would otherwise be evident. Jesus himself declares in John 3:19: “The light has come into the world, and people loved the darkness rather than the light because their works were evil.”

**The Unpardonable Sin:** Jesus’s warning about blasphemy against the Holy Spirit (Mark 3:28–29) refers to the willful attribution of God’s clear work to Satan. Applied to the resurrection, this suggests that to confront the historical and spiritual evidence and then attribute it to deceit or delusion constitutes the same category of ultimate rejection. According to John 16:8–11, the Spirit’s role is to convict the world; to resist that conviction is to remain under condemnation.

**Ancient and Modern Roots:** The pattern of rejection is ancient. In Acts 17:32, when Paul presents the resurrection to the philosophers of Athens, “some mocked.” This mingling of intellectual disdain and moral resistance to a living Lord is the same phenomenon observed today. The scriptures also warn against those who are “always learning and never able to arrive at a knowledge of the truth” (2 Timothy 3:7) — those whose rejection is not sophisticated but born of a simple love of sin.

**The Final Judgment:** The endpoint of the scriptural diagnosis is not mere disagreement but eternal sentencing. 2 Thessalonians 1:7–9 describes Jesus returning “in flaming fire, inflicting vengeance” on those who disobey the gospel. John 3:18 declares that whoever does not believe is “condemned already, because he has not believed in the name of the only Son of God.” The rejection of the risen Son is thus framed as the ultimate, self-chosen tragedy.

**Balance in Kind:** Modern skeptical discourse often pathologizes religious belief as delusion or infantile wish-fulfillment. Applying the same hermeneutic of suspicion in reverse — diagnosing unbelief as moral suppression — is intellectually symmetrical and fair. Both sides present a totalizing critique of the other; neutrality is an illusion.

